        <div class="beginner-note-content">
            <h4>Think of Databases Like Digital Filing Cabinets</h4>
            <p><strong>Databases = Organized storage systems for your application's data</strong></p>
            <p><strong>Simple analogy:</strong></p>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Database</strong> = Filing cabinet with labeled drawers</li>
                <li><strong>Table</strong> = Folder within a drawer (Products, Users, Orders)</li>
                <li><strong>Row</strong> = Individual document in a folder (specific product, user)</li>
                <li><strong>Column</strong> = Information category on the document (Name, Price, Email)</li>
                <li><strong>Entity Framework</strong> = Your personal assistant who knows exactly where everything is filed</li>
            </ul>
            <p><strong>In .NET terms:</strong> Databases store your application's data permanently, and Entity Framework helps your C# code talk to the database!</p>
        </div>
    </div>

    <div class="important-note">
        <h4><i class="fas fa-exclamation-triangle"></i> Database Selection Guide</h4>
        <p>When starting a new .NET project, choose your database based on your needs:</p>
        <ul>
            <li><strong>SQL Server</strong> - Best for Windows/enterprise applications</li>
            <li><strong>SQLite</strong> - Perfect for learning, testing, or small projects</li>
            <li><strong>PostgreSQL</strong> - Great for cross-platform and cloud applications</li>
        </ul>
    </div>

